<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="7" pageNumber="74" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="74">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="7" pageNumber="74">
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" genus="Dendrostoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Dendrostoma castaneae" order="Diaporthales" pageId="7" pageNumber="74" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="castaneae">Dendrostoma castaneae</taxonomicName>
is the most common species in this genus occurring on the host 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Castanea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Castanea mollissima" order="Fagales" pageId="7" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mollissima">Castanea mollissima</taxonomicName>
in China and is associated with canker symptoms on stems and branches. As shown in Fig. 2, 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" genus="Dendrostoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Dendrostoma castaneae" order="Diaporthales" pageId="7" pageNumber="74" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="castaneae">Dendrostoma castaneae</taxonomicName>
is the closest relative of 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. castaneicola" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="castaneicola">
<pageBreakToken pageId="8" pageNumber="75" start="start">D</pageBreakToken>
. castaneicola
</taxonomicName>
; however, they can be distinguished by conidial width (2.2-2.7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. castaneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="castaneae">D. castaneae</taxonomicName>
vs. 3.2-3.8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. castaneicola" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="castaneicola">D. castaneicola</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
